'''Lottery.com''' (AutoLotto, Inc.) is an online mobile [[lottery]] ticket management system for lottery players. The company has created a mobile app that lets users scan and check paper tickets for winnings and, in some states, play [[Powerball]] and [[Mega Millions]] on their mobile device. <ref name="auto">{{Cite web|url=https://techcrunch.com/2016/06/07/autolotto-launches-its-mobile-powerball-app/|title=AutoLotto launches its mobile Powerball app|last=Kolodny|first=Lora|website=TechCrunch|access-date=2017-01-16}}</ref>
==History==
[https://lottery.com Lottery.com], formerly AutoLotto, was founded in February 2015<ref name="auto1">{{cite web|last1=Kolodny|first1=Lora|title=AutoLotto launches its mobile Powerball app|url=https://techcrunch.com/2016/06/07/autolotto-launches-its-mobile-powerball-app/|website=TechCrunch|publisher=TechCrunch|accessdate=7 June 2016}}</ref> and launched in [[New Hampshire]] in June 2016.<ref>{{cite web|last1=Kolodny|first1=Lora|title=AutoLotto launches its mobile Powerball app|url=https://techcrunch.com/2016/06/07/autolotto-launches-its-mobile-powerball-app/|website=Techcrunch|publisher=AOL Inc.|accessdate=19 June 2016}}</ref> The Lottery.com app allows users to play the lottery from their smartphone or tablet. By November 2015, the company had raised $2.4 million in seed funding from [[500 Startups]] accelerators and Aurum Partners, an investment firm linked to the [[San Francisco 49ers]].<ref>{{cite web|last1=Kolodny|first1=Laura|title=AutoLotto Raises $2.4 Million for Mobile Powerball App|url=https://blogs.wsj.com/venturecapital/2015/11/02/autolotto-raises-2-4-million-for-mobile-powerball-app/|website=Wall Street Journal|publisher=Wall Street Journal|accessdate=15 May 2016}}</ref>
In July 2017, the mobile lottery service announced its $17 million Series A<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.cnbc.com/2017/07/10/a-mobile-powerball-app-wants-to-help-millennials-buy-lottery-tickets.html|title=A mobile Powerball app wants to help millennials buy lottery tickets|website=CNBC|last=Kolodny|first=Lora|date=2017-07-10|access-date=2017-07-10}}</ref> funding round. The investment was led by a series of private, strategic investors to support the growth and expansion of the company’s mobile app, which allows users to play the Powerball and get lottery results on their phone. In August 2017, AutoLotto officially rebranded as Lottery.com and published their new website, [https://lottery.com lottery.com]. The Lottery.com app is available nationwide with lottery ticket scanning and tracking abilities.
The startup has created a mobile app that lets users scan and check paper tickets for winnings and, in some states, play Powerball and Mega Millions on their smartphones. To stay in compliance with lottery laws, Lottery.com has to operate physical offices in every state where its users play tickets. The company aims to work with state lottery commissions and lottery directors, offices of the governor and attorney general, and other relevant legislators before going live.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.benzinga.com/trading-ideas/long-ideas/17/09/10076743/lotteries-go-online-lottery-coms-ceo-talks-about-changing-th|title=Lotteries Go Online {{!}} Benzinga |website=Benzinga |language=en-US|access-date=2017-09-24}}</ref>
More recently, they’ve expanded their platform to support charitable giving and more global games of chance. Through government lotteries, NGOs, and private charitable giving, they facilitate community renewal. Current partners include [[Akon]], [[Rihanna]]’s Clara Lionel Foundation, and [[United Nations]] Sustainability Global Index Institute.
