{{Infobox television | show_name = Go-Go Boy Interrupted | image = Go-Go Boy Interrupted (2014).png | caption = | genre = {{Plainlist| * [[Web series]] * [[LGBT]] * [[Comedy]] }} | creator = [[Jimmy Fowlie]] | based_on = | writer = Jimmy Fowlie | director = [[Jordan Black (actor)|Jordan Black]] | opentheme = | endtheme = | composer = | country = United States | language = English | num_seasons = 2 | num_episodes = 21 | list_episodes = | starring = {{Plainlist| * Jimmy Fowlie * [[Drew Droege]] * [[Lynne Marie Stewart]] * [[Mitch Silpa]] }} | producer = | editor = Mike Carrier | cinematography = Nathan Warburton | company = | runtime = 3-5 minutes | channel = [[YouTube]] | first_aired = October 7, 2014 | last_aired = July 5, 2016 | preceded_by = | followed_by = | related = | website = http://www.gogoboyinterrupted.com/#home }}
'''''Go-Go Boy Interrupted''''' is an [[LGBT]]-themed comedy [[web series]] that premiered on [[YouTube]] in October 2014. Adapted from a [[The Groundlings|Groundlings]] [[sketch comedy]] act of the same name, the series stars and was created by [[Jimmy Fowlie]]. It chronicles the adventures of Danny Carter, a 30-year-old "washed up" male [[go-go dancer]]. Fowlie commented on each of the first seven episodes via a column at [[HuffingtonPost.com]] as they were released.
==Overview== In the series, Fowlie portrays Danny Carter, a 30-year-old "washed up" male go-go dancer who "must discover a way to find his 'purpose' and survive within a different lifestyle as he moves on from go-going."<ref name="HP 2014-05">{{cite web |url=http://www.huffingtonpost.com/2014/05/27/go-go-boy-interrupted_n_5359712.html |title=Go See 'Go-Go Boy Interrupted' Sketch Show Created By Jimmy Fowlie |work=[[The Huffington Post]] |first=James |last=Nichols |date=May 27, 2014 |accessdate=November 23, 2014}}</ref><ref name="Advocate 2014-10">{{cite web |url=http://www.advocate.com/arts-entertainment/hot-sheet/2014/10/23/hot-sheet-october-24-2014?page=0,1 |title=Hot Sheet: Divas and Demons |work=[[The Advocate (LGBT magazine)|The Advocate]] |first=Daniel |last=Reynolds |date=October 24, 2014 |accessdate=November 23, 2014}}</ref> Based on Fowlie's experience as a go-go dancer in [[West Hollywood]] while attending the [[University of Southern California]], the series asks the question, "What happens next after a go-go boy ages out of his profession?"<ref name="HP 2014-05"/><ref name="Groundlings 2014">{{cite web |url=http://www.groundlings.com/performers/performer-details.aspx?performerID=492 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140720074414/http://groundlings.com/performers/performer-details.aspx?performerID=492 |title=Teachers: Jimmy Fowlie (2014) |publisher=The Groundlings |archivedate=July 20, 2014 |accessdate=November 24, 2014}}</ref> Fowlie told ''[[The Huffington Post]]'' in 2014:
{{Quote|In college I had worked as a go-go boy at this really popular club — and it was such an interesting world with outrageous characters: larger than life drag queens and 19-year-old party boys ... it just got me thinking — what happens when the party is over and someone can't leave? Dancing at a club doesn't give you any "real world skills". In other words, just like my degree in theater, it is worthless. When gay guys are using their youth and sexuality as currency, what happens when you get "aged out" of your career?<ref name="HP 2014-05"/>}}
Fowlie first performed ''Go-Go Boy Interrupted'' in June 2014 as a live sketch comedy show at The Groundlings.<ref name="HP 2014-05"/><ref name="Advocate 2014-10"/><ref name="Queerty 2014-05">{{cite web |url=http://www.queerty.com/when-is-a-man-too-old-to-be-a-go-go-boy-20140529 |title=When Is A Man Too Old To Be A Go-Go Boy? |work=[[Queerty]] |first=Dan |last=Tracer |date=May 29, 2014 |accessdate=November 23, 2014}}</ref><ref name="Towle 2014-05">{{cite web |url=http://www.towleroad.com/2014/05/watch-teaser-for-new-sketch-comedy-show-go-go-boy-interrupted.html |title=Go-Go Boy Ages Out of His Career, Has to Start Over |work=[[Towleroad]] |first=Sean |last=Mandell |date=May 27, 2014 |accessdate=November 23, 2014}}</ref><ref name="WeHoville 2014-05">{{cite web |url=http://www.wehoville.com/2014/05/26/jimmy-fowlie-injects-real-life-laughter-go-go-boy-interrupted/ |title=Jimmy Fowlie Injects Real Life (and Laughter) Into ‘Go Go Boy Interrupted’ |website=WeHoville.com |date=May 26, 2014 |accessdate=November 23, 2014}}</ref> According to Fowlie, the show continued with four months of sold-out shows, and he adapted it into a web series.<ref name="About">{{cite web |url=http://www.gogoboyinterrupted.com/#about |title=About ''Go-Go Boy Interrupted'' |website=gogoboyinterrupted.com |accessdate=November 23, 2014}}</ref> The live version is ongoing, with periodic performances scheduled through 2015.<ref name="Groundlings 2014-10">{{cite web |url=http://purchase.groundlings.com/single/EventDetail.aspx?p=1411 |title=''Go-Go Boy Interrupted'' (October 13, 2014) |publisher=[[The Groundlings]] |accessdate=November 24, 2014}}</ref><ref name="Groundlings 2015-01">{{cite web |url=http://purchase.groundlings.com/single/EventDetail.aspx?p=1627 |title=''Go-Go Boy Interrupted'' (January 5, 2015) |publisher=The Groundlings |accessdate=November 24, 2014}}</ref><ref name="LAW 2015-01">{{cite web |url=http://www.laweekly.com/calendar/go-go-boy-interrupted-5322708 |title=''Go-Go Boy Interrupted'' |date=January 5, 2015 |work=[[LA Weekly]] |first=Siran |last=Babayan |accessdate=September 11, 2015}}</ref>
